In padel, Americano and Mexicano are dynamic, social tournament formats where you play individually but rotate partners and opponents. Every rally won equals 1 point for your personal score.Americano RulesFormat: Schedules are pre-set; every player partners with and plays against everyone else.Scoring: Played to a fixed number of total points per match (usually 21, 24, or 32). If a match ends 16-8, the winning pair gets 16 points and the losers get 8.Winning: The winner is the individual with the highest total points at the end of the event.Mexicano RulesFormat: The first round is random, but all following rounds are dynamically seeded by the live leaderboard.Pairings: Players are paired based on their current ranking. The top two players pair up, playing against the third and fourth, and so on.Winning: Like Americano, the player with the most accumulated points wins, but matches get progressively tighter and more competitive.Ideal SettingsGroup Size: Both formats work best with groups divisible by 4 (e.g., 8, 12, or 16 players).Duration: Matches typically last 10–15 minutes (or until the point limit is reached).If you're planning a tournament, you can track your matches using specialized platforms like the Americano Padel App or Padelfy